Cheating and Shirking: Spousal Disagreement among Ugandan Maize farmers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The household is often considered the primary unit of production in smallholder
 agriculture.
 However, to some extent, household members also compete over scarce resources
 and revenue.
 To gain a better understanding of intra-household bargaining processes,
 data on decision making, access to production assets and appropriation
 of revenue are now often collected from co-heads individually.
 Recent research has shown that answers provided by spouses on the same
 set of questions may differ substantially, and while this is partly due
 to measurement error, there is also evidence that at least part of this
 disagreement is due to differences in the information set held by the co-heads.
 Using detailed data on a large sample of monogamous smallholder maize farming
 households in eastern Uganda, we document patterns in spousal disagreement
 in decision making, reported labour time and sales.
 In two subsamples, we implement light weight interventions to test if we
 can increase reduce disagreement by increasing cooperation between spouses
 and reducing information asymmetries.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In subsistence agriculture, the prevailing unit of analysis is the agricultural
 household.
 However, these households consist of different household members, each
 with their own utility functions and access to resources.
 The preferences of the different household members may not perfectly align,
 and there may be considerable inequality in access to resources.
 This, in turn, may also result in differences in command over revenue obtained
 from selling agricultural commodities produced.
 The realization that household members compete as well as cooperate has
 led to a burgeoning literature grounded in collective bargain theory, with
 the important policy implication being that interventions may have different
 impact depending on who is targeted within the household 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "haddad1997intrahousehold"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Many interventions started to target women within households.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increased attention for the inner workings of the household farm by both
 researchers and practitioners also led to innovations in data collection
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "https://doi.org/10.1111/agec.12540"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 One example is the Women's Empowerment in Agriculture Index (WEAI), a comprehen
sive and standardized measure to directly measure womenâ€™s empowerment and
 inclusion in the agricultural sector 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "alkire2013women"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 More generally, the focus on intra-household processes has substantially
 increased the availability of data that is collected at the individual
 household member level, especially of the co-heads of the households.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Studies that collect data from male and female co-heads separately find
 that spouses often provide different answers on the most basic questions,
 such as for instance the number of household members or when asked about
 household assets.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1086/703082"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 demonstrate that while part of the this may be attributable to measurement
 error, there is also a systematic component that reflects asymmetric informatio
n within households.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a first objective of this paper, we use detailed data from both male
 and female co-heads of monogamous semi-subsistence farm households in eastern
 Uganda to contributes to a growing literature that provides insight into
 intra-household processes by collecting data from multiple household members.
 A key paper on spousal disagreement is 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1086/703082"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 It provides a theoretical framework to explain spousal disagreement in
 survey data collected at the level of the individual co-heads.
 The model differentiates between three types of bias: (1) random measurement
 error that affects both spouses symmetrically; (2) systematic error, where
 for example the male co-head always exaggerates; and (3) information asymmetrie
s.
 Using this framework, they find evidence of significant information asymmetries
 between spouses in Bangladeshi households.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Arguably the most interesting form of spousal disagreement is the one that
 stems from information asymmetries.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1086/703082"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argue that the fact that bias is larger for some assets (eg for assets
 that can be hidden more easily) than for others suggests that asymmetric
 information in the form of hidden assets and decisions is present in the
 household
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
However, while most studies on spousal disagreement seem to assume that
 information asymmetry is a sign that individuals hide resources or actions
 from other household members, information asymmetry does not always have
 to be the result of one spouse intentionally deceiving another.
 There may be other systematic biases that manifest more in one asset or
 decision category than others.
 We think of cognitive bias that may be shaped by prevailing gender norms.
 For example, when society sees spraying chemicals as a dangerous activity
 that only men should do, men may exaggerate the resources they allocated
 to this task and the decision power in this sphere.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 A number of lab-in-the-field experiments indeed confirm that household
 members conceal resources from one another 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "eg."
key "ashraf2009spousal,10.1093/wber/lhw011,castilla2013ignorance"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We contribute to this line of research by looking at disagreement with
 respect to a range of maize farming related decisions, difference in options
 on individual time allocations to particular tasks, and income hiding..
 In particular, at the plot level, we look at how decisions are made on
 a series of important agronomic practices.
 We also look at who provides labour for different agronomic activities
 such as land preparation, planting, weeding and harvesting.
 We further look at maize sales and patterns of income hiding between spouses.
 We finally collected some information on how spouses deal with agricultural
 related disagreement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As mentioned above, new ways of thinking about intra-household decision
 making had a significant impact policies and interventions.
 However, impact evaluations of interventions that explicitly target women
 within households did not always produce the expected results.
 Partly, this was explained by the fact that the pendulum may have swung
 too far the other way and the importance of cooperation within the household
 had been ignored 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "https://doi.org/10.1111/agec.12540"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Many resources are jointly owned and decisions jointly made, and so the
 clear division between man managed and women managed plots underlying bargainin
g models may be the exception rather that the rule 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doss2014owns,twyman2015gendered,doi:10.1111/dpr.12243"
literal "true"

\end_inset

